Let us next examine solutions with non-trivial gauge fields
on the D7 brane.
Here, we consider the U-shaped solution with $c_\pm\ne 0$ and
 $c_\tau=0$.
In this case, the turning point $u_*$ is related to $c_y$ by
\begin{eqnarray}
c_y^2=\frac{u_*^6}{R^6}\left(1+\frac{c_+ c_-}{u_*^2} \right)\ .
\end{eqnarray}
If we use the coordinate $z$ introduced in (\ref{z}), the solution
(\ref{y})--(\ref{apm}) becomes
\begin{eqnarray}
y(z)&=&
\frac{R^2}{u_*}\sqrt{1+\frac{c_+c_-}{u_*^2}}\int_0^z
\frac{dz'}{{\widetilde} F(z')}
\ ,
\label{y2}
\\
a_\pm(z)&=&a_\pm^{(0)}
\pm\frac{c_\pm}{8\pi\alpha'}
f^{(\mp)}(z)
\ ,
\label{apm2}
\end{eqnarray}
where we have set $y_0=0$, and defined
\begin{eqnarray}
{\widetilde} F(z)\equiv
\sqrt{(1+z^2)\left((1+z^2)^2-\frac{u_0^4}{u_*^4}\right)
\left(3+3z^2+z^4+(2+z^2)\frac{c_+c_-}{u_*^2}\right)}\ ,
\end{eqnarray}
and
\begin{eqnarray}
f^{(\pm)}(z)
&\equiv& \exp\left(\pm 4\int_{0}^z dz'
\frac{(1+z'^2)^2}{{\widetilde} F(z')}\right)\ .
\label{fpm}
\end{eqnarray}
This function (\ref{fpm}) satisfies
\begin{eqnarray}
 f^{(\pm)}(z)=f^{(\mp)}(-z)=\frac{1}{f^{(\mp)}(z)}\ ,
\end{eqnarray}
and the asymptotic behavior is
\begin{eqnarray}
f^{(+)}(z)&\simeq&
\frac{e^{\xi}}{u_*^4}\left(
u^4+c_+c_- u^2+\frac{c_+^2c_-^2}{8}
-\frac{u_0^4}{2}
\right)+{\cal O}(u^{-2})\ ,
\\
f^{(-)}(z)&\simeq&
e^{-\xi}\frac{u_*^4}{u^4}+{\cal O}(u^{-6})\ ,
\end{eqnarray}
for $z=\sqrt{u^2/u_*^2-1}\rightarrow +\infty$,
where we have defined
\begin{eqnarray}
\xi \equiv
4\int_{u_*}^\infty du\left(
\frac{u^4}{F(u)}-\frac{1}{u}
\right)
= 4\int_0^\infty dz\left(\frac{(1+z^2)^2}{{\widetilde} F(z)}-\frac{z}{1+z^2}\right)
 \ .
\label{xi}
\end{eqnarray}


The solution (\ref{y2})--(\ref{apm2}) behaves as
\begin{eqnarray}
y(u)&\simeq&
 L-\frac{R^2}{4}\sqrt{1+\frac{c_+c_-}{u_*^2}}\frac{u_*^3}{u^4}+{\cal O}(u^{-6})
\ ,
\label{asymy}
\\
 a_+(u)&\simeq& a_+^{(0)}+\frac{c_+ e^{-\xi}}{8\pi\alpha'}
\frac{u_*^4}{u^4} +{\cal O}(u^{-6})\ ,
\label{asymap}
\\
 a_-(u)
&\simeq& \frac{c_- e^{\xi}}{8\pi\alpha'u_*^4}
\left(u^4+c_+c_-u^2+
\frac{c_+^2c_-^2}{8}-\frac{u_0^4}{2}\right)
+a_-^{(0)}
 +{\cal O}(u^{-2})\ ,
\label{asymam}
\end{eqnarray}
for $z\rightarrow +\infty$, and
\begin{eqnarray}
y(u)&\simeq&
-L+\frac{R^2}{4}\sqrt{1+\frac{c_+c_-}{u_*^2}}\frac{u_*^3}{u^4}+{\cal O}(u^{-6})\ ,
\\
 a_+(u)
&\simeq& \frac{c_+ e^{\xi}}{8\pi\alpha'u_*^4}
\left(u^4+c_+c_-u^2+\frac{c_+^2c_-^2}{8}-\frac{u_0^4}{2}\right)
+a_+^{(0)}
 +{\cal O}(u^{-2})\ ,
\label{asymap2}
\\
a_-(u)&\simeq& a_-^{(0)}+\frac{c_- e^{-\xi}}{8\pi\alpha'}
\frac{u_*^4}{u^4} +{\cal O}(u^{-6})\ ,
\label{asymam2}
\end{eqnarray}
for $z\rightarrow -\infty$,
where
\begin{eqnarray}
L=
\frac{R^2}{u_*}\sqrt{1+\frac{c_+c_-}{u_*^2}}\int_0^\infty
\frac{dz}{{\widetilde} F(z)}\ .
\label{L2}
\end{eqnarray}




\section{Operators on the defects}

\label{correlators}


\subsection{Defect mode/operator map}
\label{map}

The map between operators on the defect and fields on the D7 brane when 
supersymmetry is unbroken was analyzed in \cite{Harvey:2008zz}.
Since the asymptotic behavior of the background metric (\ref{metric})
and the D7-brane configuration is the same as that used in
\cite{Harvey:2008zz}, the results can be applied to our system.

Note that the brane configuration considered in section
\ref{braneconfig} is invariant under the $SO(6)$ symmetry that rotates
the $S^5$.
Since the 3-dimensional gauge field and the fermions on the 
defects are all singlets of $SO(6)$, we are interested in the operators 
that are invariant under the $SO(6)$ symmetry.
There are four $SO(6)$ invariant defect operators, denoted
here as $J_-$, ${\cal O}_y$,  ${\cal O}_\tau$ and ${\cal O}_+$,\footnote{
They correspond to ${\cal O}^{(0)}$,
$Q_iQ_j{\cal O}^{(1)}$, $Q^{\dag i}Q^{\dag j}{\cal O}^{(1)}$, and
$Q_iQ_jQ^{\dag k}Q^{\dag l}{\cal O}^{(2)}$
in Table 4 of \cite{Harvey:2008zz}.
Note that our conventions for the light-cone coordinates are the
reversed relative to this reference, $x^\pm_{\rm here} = x^{\mp}_{\rm
there}$.}
corresponding to $SO(6)$ invariant modes on the D7 brane at $y\rightarrow +L$ in
the brane configuration in section \ref{probeD7}.
As the notation suggests, $J_-$ is (the $U(1)$ part of) the current
operator considered in (\ref{J}). 
Keeping only the gauge field $A_\mu$ ($\mu=0,1,2$) and the defect
fermion $\psi_-$ in the analysis of \cite{Harvey:2008zz}, it can be
shown that ${\cal O}_y$ corresponds to the operator defined in (\ref{Oy}),
and ${\cal O}_+$ corresponds to the dimension~5 operator (\ref{dim5op}). 
Since
${\cal O}_\tau$ involves $A_\tau$ (the $\tau$ component of the gauge field on
the D3 brane) or the derivative with respect to $\tau$, we will not
consider it in the following.
The conformal dimension of these operators and the corresponding fields
on the D7 brane are listed in Table \ref{operator}.
\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}[t]{|c|c|c|c|}
\hline
operator&$\Delta$&source&vev\\
\hline
${\cal O}_y$ &3& $y$&$y$ \\
$J_-$ &1& $a_+$&$a_-$ \\
${\cal O}_+$ &5 & $a_-$&$a_+$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\caption{Defect mode/operator map \label{operator}}
\end{table}

As suggested in this table, the sources of the operators ${\cal O}_y$, $J_-$
and ${\cal O}_+$ correspond to the leading components of the asymptotic
expansion of the fields $y$, $a_+$ and $a_-$, respectively.
$\Delta$ in the table is the conformal dimension of these operators.
Note that the leading terms for $y$, $a_+$ and $a_-$
in (\ref{asymy})--(\ref{asymam}) are ${\cal O}(u^0)$, ${\cal O}(u^0)$
and ${\cal O}(u^4)$, respectively.
Because the dimensions of the bulk objects $u$, $y$ and $a_\pm$ 
under rescalings of the boundary
are $+1$, $-1$ and $+1$, respectively, these asymptotic behaviors are 
consistent with the conformal dimensions of the sources for ${\cal O}_y$, 
$J_-$ and ${\cal O}_+$, which are $-1$, $1$ and $-3$, respectively. 
The correlation functions of these operators can be computed by the
variation of the on-shell action with respective to the sources.
The vacuum expectation values $\left\langle {{\cal O}_y}\right\rangle$, $\left\langle {J_-}\right\rangle$ and
$\left\langle {{\cal O}_+}\right\rangle$ are contained in the
${\cal O}(u^{-4})$, ${\cal O}(u^{0})$ and ${\cal O}(u^{-4})$ terms
in the asymptotic expansions of $y$, $a_-$, and $a_+$,
respectively. We will examine them in the following subsections.

The argument above can also be applied to the other defect at $y\rightarrow -L$,
and the table corresponding to Table \ref{operator} is obtained by the
replacement: ${\cal O}_y \rightarrow {\cal O}_y'$, $J_-\rightarrow J_+$, ${\cal O}_+\rightarrow {\cal O}_-$
and $a_\pm \rightarrow a_\mp$.


\subsection{Holographic renormalization}

Following the general prescription of AdS/CFT correspondence
\cite{Witten:1998qj,Gubser:1998bc}, the correlation functions are
obtained by varying the
on-shell action. We are mostly interested in the correlation functions
of the defect operators. For this purpose, one should evaluate the
on-shell DBI-CS action including the counterterms that cancel the
divergences in the on-shell action to make it well-defined.\footnote{
See, e.g. \cite{Skenderis:2002wp}
for a review of the holographic renormalization.}
The general procedure of the holographic renormalization for our system
turns out to be very complicated.\cite{futurework}
In order to avoid such complications,
we restrict our consideration to the $x^\pm$ independent
configurations, which still contain interesting information as we
will soon show.

\subsubsection{Counterterms and the on-shell action}

First, let us find the counterterms needed to cancel the
divergences.
Here, we consider the solution (\ref{y2})--(\ref{apm2}).
In this section, we allow the gauge field to depend on $x^\pm$,
while assuming that its field strength is  $x^\pm$ independent.
Then, the constant part $a_\pm^{(0)}$ in (\ref{apm2}) and
$a_u^{(0)}\equiv a_u$ can be promoted to a flat connection satisfying
\begin{eqnarray}
{\partial}_M a_N^{(0)}-{\partial}_N a_M^{(0)}=0\ .
\label{flatcon}
\end{eqnarray}
As we will see in section \ref{bdrycond},
$a_\pm^{(0)}$ should not diverge at $z\rightarrow\pm\infty$
so that the boundary condition is consistent
with the variational principle.

Inserting the solution (\ref{y2})--(\ref{apm2})
into the DBI-CS action (\ref{DBI2})--(\ref{CS2}), 
and using (\ref{detM2}), the on-shell action is
evaluated as
\begin{eqnarray}
S_{\rm DBI}^{\rm o.s.}&=&- T_{\rm 3d}\int d^2 x
\int_{z_-}^{z_+}dz\,\frac{u_*^2(1+z^2)^3}{R{\widetilde} F(z)}\ ,
\label{onshellDBI}
\\
S_{\rm CS}^{\rm o.s.}&=&
\frac{N}{8\pi}\int d^2x \int_{z_-}^{z_+} dz\,
\frac{(1+z^2)^2}{{\widetilde} F(z)}
\left(
\frac{a_-^{(0)}c_+}{2\pi\alpha'} f^{(-)}(z)
-
\frac{a_+^{(0)}c_-}{2\pi\alpha'} f^{(+)}(z)
-\frac{c_+c_-}{2(2\pi\alpha')^2}
\right)\ ,
\label{onshellCS}
\end{eqnarray} 
where $z_\pm$ is the UV cut-off introduced
to regularize the divergence at $z\rightarrow\pm\infty$.
It can be easily seen that both (\ref{onshellDBI}) and (\ref{onshellCS})
are divergent both in the limit $z_+\rightarrow\infty$ and $z_-\rightarrow -\infty$.
The divergent terms at $z_+\rightarrow\infty$ are
\begin{eqnarray}
S_{\rm DBI}^{\rm o.s.}|_{z_+\rightarrow\infty}&\simeq& -T_{\rm 3d}\int d^2 x
\frac{1}{2R}
\left(u_{\rm max}^2-c_+c_-
\log u_{\rm max}\right) +\mbox{finite}\ ,
\label{SDBIdiv1}
\\
 S_{\rm CS}^{\rm o.s.}|_{z_+\rightarrow\infty} &\simeq&
\frac{N}{8\pi}\int d^2 x
\left(
-a_+^{(0)}\frac{c_- e^\xi}{8\pi\alpha'u_*^4}
\left(u_{\rm max}^4+c_+c_-u_{\rm max}^2
\right)
-\frac{c_+c_-}{2(2\pi\alpha')^2}\log u_{\rm max}
\right) +\mbox{finite}\ ,
{\nonumber}\\
\label{SCSdiv1}
\end{eqnarray}
where $u_{\rm max}\equiv u_*\sqrt{1+z_+^2}$. 
Similarly, the divergent terms at
$z_-\rightarrow -\infty$ are
\begin{eqnarray}
S_{\rm DBI}^{\rm o.s.}|_{z_-\rightarrow-\infty}&\simeq& -T_{\rm 3d}\int d^2 x
\frac{1}{2R}
\left(u_{\rm max}^2-c_+c_-
\log u_{\rm max}\right) +\mbox{finite}\ ,
\label{SDBIdiv2}
\\
 S_{\rm CS}^{\rm o.s.}|_{z_-\rightarrow-\infty} &\simeq&
\frac{N}{8\pi}\int d^2 x
\left(
-a_-^{(0)}\frac{c_+ e^\xi}{8\pi\alpha'u_*^4}
\left(u_{\rm max}^4+c_+c_-u_{\rm max}^2
\right)
-\frac{c_+c_-}{2(2\pi\alpha')^2}\log u_{\rm max}
\right) +\mbox{finite}\ ,
{\nonumber}\\
\label{SCSdiv2}
\end{eqnarray}
with $u_{\rm max}\equiv u_*\sqrt{1+z_-^2}$. 

The relation (\ref{T3d}) implies that the log divergent terms in
$S_{\rm DBI}$ and $S_{\rm CS}$ cancel each other. In order to
cancel the ${\cal O}(u_{\rm max}^2)$ term in the DBI action, we add
a counterterm of the form
\begin{eqnarray}
S_{\gamma\pm}\equiv \frac{T_{\rm 3d}R}{2}\int_{z=z_\pm}
\hspace{-2ex} d^2 x\sqrt{-\gamma}\ ,
\label{Sgamma}
\end{eqnarray}
where $\gamma=\det(\gamma_{ab})$ ($a,b=0,1$) is the determinant of the
induced metric on the 2-dimensional boundary defined at $z=z_\pm$. In
fact, the induced metric is given as
\begin{eqnarray}
 \gamma_{ab}=g_{ab}|_{z=z_\pm}=\frac{u_{\rm max}^2}{R^2}\eta_{ab}\ ,
\end{eqnarray}
and the counterterm (\ref{Sgamma}) precisely cancel
the ${\cal O}(u_{\rm max}^2)$ terms in (\ref{SDBIdiv1}) and (\ref{SDBIdiv2}).
The ${\cal O}(u_{\rm max}^4)$ and ${\cal O}(u_{\rm max}^2)$ terms in the CS term
are canceled by a counterterm of the form
\cite{Elitzur:1989nr,Davis:2007ka,Jensen:2010em,Yee:2011yn}
\begin{eqnarray}
S_{a\pm}&\equiv&\frac{N}{8\pi} \int_{z=z_\pm}
\hspace{-2ex} d^2x\sqrt{-\gamma}\,\gamma^{ab} a_aa_b
=-\frac{N}{8\pi} \int_{z=z_\pm}\hspace{-2ex}d^2x\,a_+a_-\ .
\label{Saa}
\end{eqnarray}
The on-shell value of this counterterm is
\begin{eqnarray}
&&S^{\rm o.s.}_{a\pm}{\nonumber}\\
&\simeq&
-\frac{N}{8\pi} \int_{z=z_\pm}d^2x
\left(
\mp a_\pm^{(0)}\frac{c_\mp}{8\pi\alpha'}
f^{\pm}(u_{\rm max})
+a_+^{(0)}a_-^{(0)}
-\frac{c_+c_-}{(8\pi\alpha')^2R^2}
\right)
\label{onshellSa}
\\
&\simeq&
\frac{N}{8\pi} \int_{z=z_\pm}\hspace{-2ex}d^2x
\Bigg(
a_\pm^{(0)}\frac{c_\mp}{8\pi\alpha'}
\frac{e^{\xi}}{u_*^4}\left(
u_{\rm max}^4+c_+c_- u_{\rm max}^2
+\frac{c_+^2c_-^2}{8}
-\frac{u_0^4}{2}
\right)
-a_+^{(0)}a_-^{(0)}
+\frac{c_+c_-}{(8\pi\alpha')^2}
\Bigg)\ .
{\nonumber}\\
\end{eqnarray}
Here, we omitted the terms that vanish at
$z_\pm\rightarrow\pm\infty$ ($u_{\rm max}\rightarrow\infty$). This counterterm
cancels the divergent terms in
(\ref{SCSdiv1}) and (\ref{SCSdiv2}).
Therefore, the total action we consider is\footnote{There are more
counterterms needed to cancel the divergence for the general solution
that has non-trivial $x^\pm$ dependence.\cite{futurework}
}
\begin{eqnarray}
 S_{\rm total}\equiv S_{\rm DBI}+S_{\rm CS}+S_{\gamma+}+S_{\gamma-}
+S_{a+}+S_{a-}\ .
\end{eqnarray}
Collecting the expressions (\ref{onshellDBI}),
 (\ref{onshellCS}), (\ref{Sgamma}) and (\ref{onshellSa}),
the on-shell action is evaluated as
\begin{eqnarray}
 S^{\rm o.s.}_{\rm total}
&=&-
\frac{Nu_*^2}{8\pi(2\pi\alpha')^2}\int d^2 x
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}dz
\left(\frac{(1+z^2)^2}{{\widetilde} F(z)}\left(1+z^2+\frac{c_+c_-}{2 u_*^2}\right)
-|z|\right)
{\nonumber}\\
&&
-\frac{N}{8\pi}\int d^2x
\left((a_+^{(0)}a_-^{(0)})\big|_{z\rightarrow+\infty}
+(a_+^{(0)}a_-^{(0)})\big|_{z\rightarrow-\infty}
-\frac{2c_+c_-}{(8\pi\alpha')^2}
-\frac{u_*^2}{(2\pi\alpha')^2}
\right)\ .
\label{ostotal}
\end{eqnarray}
Here, we have used the relations
\begin{eqnarray}
&& {\partial}_z f^{(\pm)}(z)=\pm 4\frac{(1+z^2)^2}{{\widetilde} F(z)}f^{(\pm)}(z)\ ,\\
&& u_{\rm max}^2=u_*^2\left(\int_{z_-}^{z_+}dz\,|z|+1\right)\ ,
\end{eqnarray}
for $z_+=-z_-=\sqrt{u_{\rm max}^2/u_*^2-1}$,
and dropped the terms proportional to
\begin{eqnarray}
\int d^2x \int_{z_-}^{z_+}dz\,{\partial}_z a_\pm^{(0)}c_\mp f^{(\pm)}(z)\ ,
\end{eqnarray}
because these terms are total derivative in the $x^\pm$ direction,
using the flatness condition (\ref{flatcon}).


\subsubsection{Boundary conditions}
\label{bdrycond}

Motivated by the asymptotic behavior of the solutions 
(\ref{asymy})--(\ref{asymam2}) 
and the consideration in section \ref{map},
we impose the boundary condition for the gauge field as 
\begin{eqnarray}
 a_\pm(x^a,z)\rightarrow {\cal A}_\pm(x^a)\ ,~~
 a_\mp(x^a,z)\frac{R^8}{u^4}
\rightarrow {\cal C}_\mp(x^a)\ ,~~~(z\rightarrow \pm\infty)\ ,
\label{abdry}
\end{eqnarray}where $a=0,1$, and ${\cal A}_\pm$ and ${\cal C}_\mp$ are fixed values.
These ${\cal A}_\pm$ and ${\cal C}_\mp$ are interpreted as the sources
that couple to the operators $J_{\mp}$ and ${\cal O}_{\pm}$ on the defects
placed at $y=y(z)|_{z\rightarrow\pm\infty}$, respectively.
Similarly, the boundary condition for the scalar field $y$ is
\begin{eqnarray}
 y(x^a,z)\rightarrow {\cal Y}^{(\pm)}(x^a)\ ,~~~(z\rightarrow\pm\infty)\ .
\label{ybdry}
\end{eqnarray}
${\cal Y}^{(\pm)}(x^a)$ is the source of ${\cal O}_y$ and ${\cal O}_y'$.

Let us check that our solution (\ref{y2})--(\ref{apm2}) and
the boundary conditions (\ref{abdry}) and (\ref{ybdry}) are
consistent with the variational principle including the contributions
from the boundaries. The variation of the action
gives surface terms as
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta S_{\rm DBI}&=&\mbox{(EOM)}
-T_{\rm 3d}
\int d^2 x\,\left[
\sqrt{-{{\cal G}}}\left(
\frac{u^2}{R^2}{\cal G}_{\rm S}^{u N}{\partial}_{N} y\,\delta y
-(2\pi\alpha')
{\cal G}_{\rm A}^{u N}\delta a_{N}
\right)\right]_{z=-\infty}^{z=+\infty}\ ,
\\
 \delta S_{\rm CS}
&=&\mbox{(EOM)}+\frac{N}{8\pi}\int d^2 x\,
\left[a_+\delta a_--a_-\delta a_+\right]_{z=-\infty}^{z=+\infty}\ ,
\\
 \delta S_{a\pm}
&=&-\frac{N}{8\pi}\int_{z\rightarrow\pm\infty}\hspace{-2ex} d^2 x\,
(a_+\delta a_-+a_-\delta a_+)\ ,
\end{eqnarray}
where $\mbox{(EOM)}$ denotes the bulk terms that give the
equations of motion {(\ref{{yEOM}})} and {(\ref{{aEOM}})}, while
${\cal G}$, ${\cal G}_{\rm S}^{MN}$ and ${\cal G}_{\rm A}^{MN}$ are defined as
in equations {(\ref{{cG}})}, {(\ref{{MS}})} and {(\ref{{MA}})}.

In Appendix \ref{eomDBI-CS},
it is shown that the gauge field $a_M$ satisfying the
equations of motion can always be decomposed as 
\begin{eqnarray}
a_M=a_M^{(0)}+b_M\ ,
\end{eqnarray}
where $a_M^{(0)}$ is a flat connection satisfying (\ref{flatcon}),
and $b_M$ is defined by
\begin{eqnarray}
 b_\pm&\equiv&
 \mp \frac{4\pi}{N}(2\pi\alpha')T_{\rm 3d}
\sqrt{-{\cal G}}\,{\cal G}_A^{u\mp}\ ,
\\
 b_u&\equiv&
  \frac{4\pi}{N}(2\pi\alpha')T_{\rm 3d}
\sqrt{-{\cal G}}\,{\cal G}_A^{+-}\ .
\end{eqnarray}
Therefore, for the on-shell configurations, the variation becomes
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta S_{\rm total}
&=&
-T_{\rm 3d}\int d^2 x\,
\left[
\sqrt{-{\cal G}}
\frac{u^2}{R^2}{\cal G}_S^{u N}{\partial}_N y\,\delta y
\right]_{z=-\infty}^{z=+\infty}
{\nonumber}\\
&&
-\frac{N}{4\pi}\int_{z\rightarrow+\infty}\hspace{-2ex} d^2 x\,
(a^{(0)}_-\delta a_+ +b_+\delta a_-)
-\frac{N}{4\pi}\int_{z\rightarrow-\infty}\hspace{-2ex} d^2 x\,
(a^{(0)}_+\delta a_- +b_-\delta a_+)
\ .
\label{surf}
\end{eqnarray}
For our solution (\ref{asymy})--(\ref{asymam2}), we have
\begin{eqnarray}
&&\sqrt{-{{\cal G}}}
\frac{u^2}{R^2}{\cal G}_S^{u N}{\partial}_N y= c_y\ ,
\\
&&b_\pm(z)=\frac{c_\pm}{8\pi\alpha'}f^{(\mp)}(z)\sim{\cal O}(u^{-4})\ ,
~~(z\rightarrow\pm\infty)\ .
\label{bp}
\end{eqnarray}
Then, the boundary conditions
(\ref{abdry}) and (\ref{ybdry}) imply that the surface terms in
(\ref{surf}) with $\delta y$ and $b_{\pm}\delta a_\mp$ vanish,
because ${\cal O}(u^0)$ terms in $\delta y$, and
 ${\cal O}(u^4)$ terms in $\delta a_\mp$ ($z\rightarrow\pm\infty$)
are zero when the sources are fixed.
In order to make sure that the surface terms in (\ref{surf}) with
$a_\mp^{(0)}\delta a_\pm$ vanish, we impose a boundary condition as
$a_\mp^{(0)}\sim{\cal O}(u^0)$ at $z\rightarrow\pm\infty$.



\subsection{Gauge invariance and anomaly }
\label{gaugeinvanom}

One may wonder the consistency of the counterterm (\ref{Saa}), because
it is not gauge invariant. In fact the counterterm (\ref{Saa}) is
needed to ensure the gauge invariance.
Let us clarify this point.
Under the gauge transformation
\begin{eqnarray}
a\rightarrow a+d\lambda\ , 
\label{gaugetrans}
\end{eqnarray}
$S_{\rm CS}$ and $S_{a\pm}$ transform as
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta_\lambda S_{\rm CS}
&=&-\frac{N}{8\pi}\left(
\int_{z\rightarrow+\infty}\hspace{-2ex}d^2x\,  \lambda f_{+-}
-\int_{z\rightarrow-\infty}\hspace{-2ex}d^2x\,  \lambda f_{+-}
\right)\ ,
\label{deltaScs}
\\
\delta_\lambda S_{a\pm}
&=&
\frac{N}{8\pi}
\int_{z\rightarrow\pm\infty}d^2x\,\left(\lambda{\partial}_+a_-+\lambda{\partial}_-a_+\right)\ .
\end{eqnarray}
Here, we have dropped the surface terms at $|x^\pm|\rightarrow\infty$.
Then, assuming that all the other counterterms are gauge invariant,
the total action transforms as
\begin{eqnarray}
 \delta_\lambda S_{\rm total}
=\frac{N}{4\pi}\left(
\int_{z\rightarrow+\infty}\hspace{-2ex}d^2x\,  \lambda {\partial}_-a_+
+\int_{z\rightarrow-\infty}\hspace{-2ex}d^2x\,  \lambda {\partial}_+a_-
\right)\ .
\label{anom1}
\end{eqnarray}
Because of the boundary condition (\ref{abdry}),
$a_\pm$ do not diverge at $z\rightarrow\pm\infty$, and
the total action is invariant under the gauge transformation with
$\lambda$ vanishing at $z\rightarrow\pm\infty$. 
Note that for general field configuration with the boundary condition
(\ref{abdry}), (\ref{deltaScs}) is non-vanishing. The gauge invariance
is guaranteed only after the counterterms $S_{a\pm}$ are added.

When the
$U(1)$ symmetry associated to the current
$J_-$ is gauged, 
the gauge transformation of this $U(1)$ symmetry
\begin{eqnarray}
 {\cal A}_+\rightarrow {\cal A}_+ +{\partial}_+ \Lambda\ ,
\label{cAgauge}
\end{eqnarray}
is realized by imposing a boundary condition for $\lambda$ as
\begin{eqnarray}
 \lambda(x^a,z)\rightarrow\Lambda(x^a)\ ,~~~(z\rightarrow +\infty)\ .
\end{eqnarray}
As we have seen in (\ref{anom1}), the D7-brane action is not invariant
under this gauge transformation and transforms as
\begin{eqnarray}
 \delta_\lambda S_{\rm total}
=\frac{N}{4\pi}
\int_{z\rightarrow +\infty}\hspace{-2ex}d^2x\,  \Lambda {\partial}_-{\cal A}_+
\ .
\label{anom2}
\end{eqnarray}
This expression precisely agrees with the anomalous transformation of
the generating function for correlation functions in the
dual field theory induced by one loop diagrams of the chiral fermion on
the defect.
In fact, omitting the supergravity action,
the on-shell value of the action $S_{\rm total}$ is identified as
\begin{eqnarray}
 e^{iS_{\rm total}^{\rm o.s.}({\cal A})}
\propto \int{\cal D}\psi{\cal D} A\, e^{iS_{\rm 3d}(\psi,A,{\cal A})}\ ,
\end{eqnarray}
where $S_{\rm 3d}(\psi,A,{\cal A})$ is the action of the 3-dimensional
$SU(N)$ YM-CS theory with defect given by the sum of
(\ref{SA}) (with $k=1$, $k'=0$), (\ref{Spsi}) and (\ref{AJ}).
Then, the gauge transformation (\ref{cAgauge}) of this equation
and (\ref{anom2}) imply the anomaly equation

\footnote{
See \cite{Jensen:2010em,Yee:2011yn}
and section \ref{anomsbem} for closely related derivations.
}

\begin{eqnarray}
{\partial}_+\left\langle {J_-}\right\rangle = 
-2{\partial}_+\left\langle {J^+}\right\rangle = 
\frac{N}{2\pi}{\partial}_-{\cal A}_+\ ,
\label{anomeq}
\end{eqnarray}

reproducing equation~{(\ref{{anomaly}})} for the case $k-k'=1$.



\subsection{Correlation functions}

Comparing the asymptotic behavior (\ref{asymy})--(\ref{asymam2})
of the solution to the boundary conditions (\ref{abdry})--(\ref{ybdry}),
the sources in our configuration are identified as
\begin{eqnarray}
 {\cal A}_\pm =a_\pm^{(0)}|_{z\rightarrow\pm\infty}\ ,~~~
{\cal C}_\mp=\frac{c_\mp}{8\pi\alpha'}\frac{R^8}{u_*^4}e^\xi\ ,~~~
{\cal Y}^{(\pm)}=\pm L\ .
\end{eqnarray}
The correlation functions can be computed by differentiating the
on-shell action (\ref{ostotal}) with respect to these sources.
Using the expressions (\ref{surf})--(\ref{bp}),
the one point functions for the operators at $y=+L$ ($z\rightarrow+\infty$)
are obtained as
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle {{\cal O}_y}\right\rangle&=&\frac{\delta S_{\rm total}^{\rm o.s.}}{\delta{\cal Y}^{(+)}}
=-T_{\rm 3d} c_y
=-\frac{N}{8\pi(2\pi\alpha')^2}\frac{u_*^3}{R^2}
\sqrt{1+\frac{c_+c_-}{u_*^2}}\ ,
\label{VEVOy}
\\
\left\langle {J^+}\right\rangle&=&\frac{\delta S_{\rm total}^{\rm o.s.}}{\delta{\cal A}_+}
=-\frac{N}{4\pi}a^{(0)}_-|_{z\rightarrow +\infty}\ ,
\label{VEVJm}
\\
\left\langle {{\cal O}_+}\right\rangle&=&\frac{\delta S_{\rm total}^{\rm o.s.}}{\delta{\cal C}_-}
=-\frac{N}{4\pi}\frac{c_+}{8\pi\alpha'}\frac{u_*^4}{R^8} e^{-\xi}\ .
\label{VEVOp}
\end{eqnarray}

The two (or higher) point functions can be obtained by differentiating
these expressions with respect to the sources.


\subsubsection{Condensation of ${\cal O}_y$}

In particular, (\ref{VEVOy}) implies that
$\left\langle {{\cal O}_y}\right\rangle$ is non-zero even when
the external sources ${\cal A}_\pm$ and ${\cal C}_\pm$ are turned off.
When ${\cal C}_\pm=0$, as depicted in Fig.~\ref{FigOy},
the absolute value $|\left\langle {{\cal O}_y}\right\rangle|$ is a monotonically
decreasing function of $L$ and the asymptotic value is
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle {{\cal O}_y}\right\rangle|_{{\cal C}_\pm=0,L\rightarrow\infty} 
=-\frac{N}{8\pi(2\pi\alpha')^2}\frac{u_0^3}{R^2}
=-\frac{N \lambda_{\rm 3d} M_{\rm KK}^2}{64\pi^2}\ ,
\end{eqnarray}
where $\lambda_{\rm 3d}\equiv g_{\rm 3d}^2 N=g_s M_{\rm KK}N$
is the 't Hooft coupling.

